<subSubSection id="C9AE24C71DB328554D01A54026A50FBC" lastPageId="18" lastPageNumber="47" pageId="17" pageNumber="46" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="707CFD4347905680A399FE7ACF71A9CE" pageId="17" pageNumber="46">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="57AD4765EE9E5278C8FE5519EBE1C865" pageId="18" pageNumber="47">
<taxonomicName id="2A07ECC938408F0854BD6EF3B7DBF067" authority="Pic, 1921" authorityName="Pic" authorityYear="1921" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" genus="Platerodrilus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Platerodrilus luteus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="47" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="luteus">
<pageBreakToken id="14D94749399EA15DB57E35B3E2913722" pageId="18" pageNumber="47" start="start">Platerodrilus</pageBreakToken>
luteus
</taxonomicName>
resembles in general appearance the syntopically occurring 
<taxonomicName id="BBB29DFE45159B3F9E84651FF753587B" authority="Pic, 1921" authorityName="Pic" authorityYear="1921" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" genus="Platerodrilus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Platerodrilus robinsoni" order="Coleoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="47" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="robinsoni">Platerodrilus robinsoni</taxonomicName>
, but these species are distantly related according to the recovered molecular phylogeny (Fig. 1). The male of 
<taxonomicName id="DCDE2413BFA4B06A0859A1C0D8D0E6A8" authority="Pic, 1921" authorityName="Pic" authorityYear="1921" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" genus="Platerodrilus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Platerodrilus luteus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="47" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="luteus">Platerodrilus luteus</taxonomicName>
differs from similarly coloured Sumatran 
<taxonomicName id="3B8B9672634813EEF9B0B4CBD3D32080" authority="Pic, 1921" authorityName="Pic" authorityYear="1921" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" genus="Platerodrilus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Platerodrilus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="47" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Platerodrilus</taxonomicName>
in the very wide and broadly emarginate phallobase (Fig. 67).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="A4A2D53E134D3AAC8D7BEA700E673B5B" lastPageId="19" lastPageNumber="48" pageId="18" pageNumber="47" type="description">
<paragraph id="235E1623A792EFE0EB38CF70587A2D90" pageId="18" pageNumber="47">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="BA898C7E53C5E8C9266BCB0AA2F2467C" lastPageId="19" lastPageNumber="48" pageId="18" pageNumber="47">
Body black, head dark brown, pronotum and elytra orange; antennae, and legs dark brown to black (Fig. 8). Head small, antennal tubercles weak, eyes hemispherically prominent, frontal interocular distance 2.8 times maximum eye diameter. Antennae slender, compressed, densely pubescent, antennomere 3 1.5 times longer than antennomere 2. Pronotum transverse, 1.7 times wider than long, frontal angles inconspicuous, lateral margins slightly convex, posterior angles acute (Fig. 23). Elytra 
<pageBreakToken id="377AA4528F90C4593A545246A2302127" pageId="19" pageNumber="48" start="start">parallel-sided</pageBreakToken>
, 3.7 times longer than width at humeri, elytral costae weak, covered with dense pubescence. Male genitalia with curved phallus; parameres short, rounded, with slender membranous processes; phallobase wide, deeply emarginate (Fig. 67-68).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="F3C12D19A4B9A40196D3B1836110BE6F" pageId="19" pageNumber="48" type="measurements">
